07363nam a22009735i 9781442682979DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162004onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)999373816  a97814426829797 a10.3138/97814426829792doi  a(DE-B1597)465083  a(OCoLC)944177273  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aMED0360002bisacsh04a362.100aUsing Knowledge and Evidence in Health Care :bMultidisciplinary Perspectives /ced. by Francois Champagne, Louise Lemieux-Charles. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (290 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Towards a Broader Understanding of the Use of Knowledge and Evidence in Health Care -- t1. A Knowledge Utilization Perspective on Fine-Tuning Dissemination and Contextualizing Knowledge -- t2. A Sociological Perspective on the Transfer and Utilization of Social Scientific Knowledge for Policy-Making -- t3. A Political Science Perspective on Evidence-Based Decision-Making -- t4. An Organizational Science Perspective on Information, Knowledge, Evidence, and Organizational Decision-Making -- t5. An Innovation Diffusion Perspective on Knowledge and Evidence in Health Care -- t6. A Program Evaluation Perspective on Processes, Practices, and Decision-Makers -- t7. A Cognitive Science Perspective on Evidence-Based Decision-Making in Medicine -- t8. An Informatics Perspective on Decision Support and the Process of Decision-Making in Health Care -- t9. An Evidence-Based Medicine Perspective on the Origins, Objectives, Limitations, and Future Developments of the Movement -- t10. A Nursing and Allied Health Sciences Perspective on Knowledge Utilization -- tPostscript: Understanding Evidence-Based Decision-Making – or, Why Keyboards Are Irrational -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the clinical, management, and policy levels, the use of knowledge and evidence in health care has become a worldwide priority. The contributors to Using Knowledge and Evidence in Health Care seek to broaden our understanding of the complexity involved in health care decision-making by integrating social science knowledge and exploring some of the challenges and limits of evidence in different health care contexts. Louise Lemieux-Charles and François Champagne have brought together an esteemed group of scholars to provide a conceptual framework that illustrates the factors critical to analysing and optimizing the use of knowledge and evidence. Previous studies have focused primarily on the medical literature without acknowledging the social sciences tradition. With its integration of works from political science, public policy, informatics, and other disciplines, Using Knowledge and Evidence in Health Care provides a bridge between both worlds. By bringing together different views on the topic, the volume goes beyond strict disciplinary boundaries to provide the fullest exploration of knowledge and evidence in health care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEvidence-based medicine. 0aMedical carexDecision making. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aArocha, Jose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, G. Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnsley, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolduc, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChampagne, Francois, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChampagne, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aContandriopoulos,